  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      This project is focused on the neural and behavioral correlates of two different videos games
      that will be used as training tools. The two video games, developed by the Games Learning
      Society research group at the University of Wisconsin-Madison (UW) and the Wisconsin
      Institute for Discovery, are tailored to train mindfulness, particularly the regulation of
      attention; and prosocial behavior, especially sensitivity to others, in adolescents. This
      study will evaluate the hypothesis that systematic playing of mindfulness and prosocial games
      will change brain function in specific attentional, social and emotional circuits in
      potentially beneficial ways, and will impact performance on cognitive tasks of attention, and
      on measures of social cue perception and the propensity to share and behave altruistically.
      The investigators will employ behavioral and functional MRI-based neuroimaging measures to
      evaluate the investigators hypothesis.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
